		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="fake foot approaching a stingray in a tank" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-stingray-biomechanics-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">A fake foot helps researchers at California State University, Long Beach, determine how stingrays react when they come in contact with people. Photo by Thomas R. Cordova/<em>Long Beach Post</em></div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">A Step Forward in Stingray Science</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">A California researcher and his team simulate stepping on round rays to learn more about how, why, and when the animals strike.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/katharine-gammon/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Katharine Gammon</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						June 11, 2024 | 1,700 words, about 9 minutes
					</aside>

					
